1
00:00:03,031 --> 00:00:06,982
In 1940, the Tacoma Narrows Bridge looked like the future.

2
00:00:07,863 --> 00:00:15,804
It was long, slender, cheaper than the original conservative design, and beautiful enough to make its movement famous.

3
00:00:16,727 --> 00:00:19,554
People called it Galloping Gertie.

4
00:00:20,344 --> 00:00:22,871
But the wind on collapse day was not extraordinary.

5
00:00:23,673 --> 00:00:26,181
The bridge had already survived stronger autumn winds.

6
00:00:27,042 --> 00:00:30,573
The hidden problem was what the bridge did to the air after it started moving.

7
00:00:31,535 --> 00:00:35,906
Its shallow solid plate girder deck was too flexible in torsion.

8
00:00:35,887 --> 00:00:43,326
Once the roadway began to twist, the motion changed the airflow, and the changed airflow fed the next twist.

9
00:00:44,329 --> 00:00:51,546
Engineers were studying the motion, but the design culture had not yet made dynamic aerodynamic testing routine for bridges like this.

10
00:00:52,670 --> 00:00:54,173
The bridge did not just meet wind.

11
00:00:55,036 --> 00:00:57,502
It entered a behavior its own design made possible.

12
00:00:58,524 --> 00:01:01,792
Small causes, massive consequences.
